meta {
  name: Lenient Accepts Bogus Status
  type: http
  seq: 2
}

post {
  url: {{baseUrl}}/fhir/ConceptMap?_validate=lenient
  body: json
  auth: none
}

headers {
  Content-Type: application/fhir+json
  Accept: application/fhir+json
}

body:json {
  {
    "resourceType": "ConceptMap",
    "url": "http://example.org/cm/lenient-accept",
    "status": "not-a-real-status",
    "group": [
      {
        "source": "http://s",
        "target": "http://t",
        "element": [
          {"code": "A", "target": [{"code": "B", "relationship": "equivalent"}]}
        ]
      }
    ]
  }
}

assert {
  res.status: eq 201
  res.body.resourceType: eq ConceptMap
  res.body.status: eq not-a-real-status
}

docs {
  # Lenient validation accepts the same body the strict tier rejected

  Adding `?_validate=lenient` opts the create/update into the lenient
  validator. Lenient mode skips:

  - status value-set binding (here we send `not-a-real-status` and it's
    persisted verbatim)
  - relationship vocabulary check (R4 `equivalence` spellings like
    `subsumes`, `wider`, `narrower` are accepted)
  - unmapped.mode enum

  but **still enforces structural invariants**: required cardinalities, the
  code+valueSet mutual-exclusion on Element, and that every target has
  some qualifier (relationship or equivalence).

  This is the path the fixture loader uses for the docs/conceptmap-*.json
  corpus — several of those examples violate their own spec slightly.
  Without lenient mode, fixtures couldn't load via the HTTP API; with it,
  the strict default still protects normal client writes.
}
